snippet.textDisplay: I definitely believe that martial arts can help you with every difficulty you can have in regards to your mental, physical, spiritual, and emotional growth. Some people think that it would be counterproductive to take martial arts if you have anger problems, for example, or have a tumultuous inner struggle but it teaches you how to conquer yourself and being peace within first and foremost. I had a really rough time just even existing because of childhood sexual trauma. My mother got me all the help she could with therapy and every kind of support she could find. But I was so fucked up I couldn't really function. I was caustic in ever way. It wasn't until my friends talked me into joining their taekwondo school. I can't even begin to describe the amount of healing it brought me. I remember times where I could only cry during classes because there was just so much that I couldn't process or even speak about. It was like being completely rewired as a person. I stopped shutting down, stopped hating everybody and everything, stopped hating myself. I learned to respect myself and others. I learned that if I can't help someone then at the very least, do not harm them, myself especially. So to hear Robert Downey Jr's recovery was dependent on what he was taught and given from martial arts it resonates with me in such a tangible way.

snippet.textDisplay: Tropic Thunder is, in my world, one of those great silly satires. I know this may not be popular opinion, but I put it on par with Mel Brooks's creations. Mel Brooks and Ben Stiller both have a way of poking fun at tropes with a disarming humor that allows you to drop your guard and reflect on things in a way you might not have in any other way. That's something I've always been able to appreciate in any great work of comedy. Kiss Kiss Bang Bang...don't even get me started! I love a good noir sleuth movie and it was witty and fresh and not at all what you would expect. Val Kilmer and Robert Downey Jr. were just amazing together. John Favreau's amazing, too. Without him, there is no fucking way we would have been given the marvel cinematic universe in the way that we deserved. It was one of those things where it had to be done at the right time with the right crew and right actors. No better case for this can be made than with the Spiderman movies.
